  "output": "This is a Python job-scraping pipeline (SQLite + async HTTP fetchers), not a web app — there's no React/frontend anywhere (no `package.json`, no `.jsx`/`.tsx`, just static HTML CV templates), so that part of your checklist doesn't apply. Here's what I found grounded in the actual code:\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job fetched (can be thousands across `sources.yaml`'s ATS boards), it runs a separate `SELECT` and then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nThat's 2N individual statement executions instead of a bulk read + bulk write. Fix: load all existing `(key, content_hash)` pairs into a dict once, diff in Python, then use `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, to_insert, to_update, to_touch = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            to_touch.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if to_touch:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", to_touch)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nWith one board alone (Microsoft/Amazon cap at 40 pages × 10 = 400 rows) this turns hundreds of round-trip statement executions into 1 SELECT + up to 3 `executemany` batches.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)`/`_compile(include)` **inside** that per-job call — recompiling the same regex list from scratch for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...) for j in jobs]\n```\n\nWith 1000+ fetched jobs and even a handful of keywords, that's thousands of unnecessary `re.compile` calls. Fix: compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n(Change the type hints from `list[str]` to `list[re.Pattern]` accordingly.)\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — uncached `Job.key` / `Job.content_hash` properties\n\n`models.py:55-69` — `key` and `content_hash` are plain `@property`, so every access recomputes (sha256 hash for `content_hash`). In the current `diff()` flow, a **changed** job has its hash computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update` → `to_row()` — same hash, computed twice. Also `job.key` gets recomputed on every `to_row()` call and every dict lookup.\n\nCheap fix — use `functools.cached_property` (works fine even with `@dataclass(slots=True)` if you add `__dict__` via a plain property caching pattern, or since it's `slots=True`, cache manually):\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\nLow-impact at current volumes (a few thousand jobs/run), but free to fix and avoids doubling hash work in `_update`.\n\n## 4. SQLite concurrency — no WAL mode\n\n`store.py`'s own docstring for `next_seq` (line 111-116) says parallel pipeline workers claim counters via `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`, meaning concurrent writers are expected. The connection is opened with SQLite's default rollback-journal mode, which takes an exclusive lock for the entire write transaction — so concurrent workers will serialize/block on every commit, not just on `next_seq`. Add once in `__init__`:\n\n```python\nself.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")\nself.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL\")\n```\n\nWAL lets readers proceed while a writer commits, which matters given your memory note about [[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]] from a prior session.\n\n## Not applicable here\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend framework in this repo.\n- **Memory leaks**: this is a short-lived CLI script per run (`pipeline.py:run` / `agent.py` subcommands), not a long-running process — no persistent leak surface. `fetch_all` correctly closes its `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` block (`fetchers.py:1144-1146`).\n\nThe N+1 in `store.py` is the highest-value fix — it's the one that scales with job volume as you add more ATS sources to `sources.yaml`. Want me to implement it?\n",
